        <p xml:id="auto_1fkmy3pr">
          ♦ Generally, if the lengths of the two sides and an included angle of a triangle are given, then the area of the triangle is <m>\text{A} = \frac{1}{2}\textbf{ab}\textbf{sin}\theta</m>. Where <m>\textbf{ b } \text{is the base and } \textbf{ h }  \text{ height.}</m>
        </p>
       
        <exploration xml:id="auto_ujgh3fy9">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_01dhcapq">
                     <ol xml:id="auto_rbupefki">
                        <li xml:id="auto_mee37i51">
                            <p xml:id="auto_w31y8xl5">
                               Deriving the Formula: <m>\frac {1}{2}ab\, \text{sin C} </m>
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_47u8rvnc">
                                <ul xml:id="auto_7gwbwi66">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_hu1v65mj">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_h1l7fcej">
                                           Step 1:   Let's recall the Basic Formula for finding area of a triangle.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_ui2wggpy">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_llxl8e8p">
                                         Area = <m>\frac {1}{2} \times \text {Base} \times \text {Height}</m> 
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>  
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_j7ft6zod">
                            <p xml:id="auto_0ubnoy4m">
                               <m>\textbf {Step 2: Consider a Triangle with an Angle}</m>.
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_klctlr7g">
                                <ul xml:id="auto_syiwnrz3">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_8ozca6o8">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_bpbaneqw">
                                           Let's take a triangle ABC with sides <m>a </m>, <m>b </m> and included angle <m>C</m>.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_cwshuycf">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_4wexgdy0">
                                         Side<m> \, a</m> and Side <m>b</m> form the triangle.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_0rh6hqoe">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_ymu5fn9s">
                                            The height <m> h</m> is perpendicular from the top vertex to the base.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>    
                            </p>    
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_y8x5a7uk">
                            <p xml:id="auto_swz80dgl">
                                <m>\textbf {Step 3: Express Height in Terms of Sin}</m>
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_ckjmzoof">
                                <ul xml:id="auto_nu7bqwb4">
                                    <li xml:id="auto_3vov2jt4">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_yv76klad">
                                           Using trigonometry, we know that in a right-angled triangle:
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_n5pk6wbw">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_kq65h0yx">
                                            <m>\text{sin} \,\theta = \frac{\text{Hypotenuse}}{\text{Opposite}}</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_3jvs4zwa">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_bhlmq502">
                                            In our case, the height <m>h</m> is the <m>\textbf{opposite side}</m> of angle <m>C</m>, and side <m>b</m> is the <m>\textbf{hypotenuse}</m>.
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                    <li xml:id="auto_mwshzuig">
                                        <p xml:id="auto_umhl5led">
                                         So, we can write it as:
                                        </p>
                                        <p xml:id="auto_rcr35sor">
                                            <m> h = b \text{ sin} \, C</m>
                                        </p>
                                    </li>
                                </ul>
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_22rtecas">
                        <p xml:id="auto_hijq69pa">
                            <m>\textbf {Step 4: Substitute into the Area Formula}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_173ledgg">
                            <ul xml:id="auto_294przis">
                                <li xml:id="auto_nbrz9ce3">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_9j4nxlv8">
                                        Now, take the basic Formula for finding area of a triangle;
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_lx78e7hp">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_uc7h1b9l">
                                        Substituting <m>\textbf{Base}</m> and <m>\textbf{Height}  = \text{b sin C} </m> .
                                    <md>
                                      <mrow> \text{Area} =\amp \frac {1}{2} \times a \times \text{(b sin C)}</mrow>
                                      <mrow> \text{Area} = \amp  \frac {1}{2} ab \, \text{ sin C}</mrow>
                                    
                                      </md>  
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_jnxkzd1u">
                        <p xml:id="auto_4ktmng6m">
                            <m> \textbf{NOTE:}</m>
                        </p>
                        <p xml:id="auto_hbi1nktz">
                            <ul xml:id="auto_wpp6ixyf">
                                <li xml:id="auto_fis0g880">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_jzp8qvsh">
                                        <md>
                                           <mrow> \text{Area} = \amp  \frac {1}{2} ab \, \text{ sin C}</mrow>
                                        </md>
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                                <li xml:id="auto_lem42cq6">
                                    <p xml:id="auto_mt6nwtlo">
                                        This formula is useful when we know two sides of a triangle and the angle between them instead of the height..
                                    </p>
                                </li>
                            </ul>
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    </ol>    

                </p>
            </statement>
        </exploration>
        <example xml:id="auto_1onu5nu3">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_4abiaqip">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_go6l1cyh">
                       1.A triangle HFG has sides <m>10 \text{ cm}, 7 \text{ cm and } 9 \text{ cm.}</m> Find:</p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_8mozo9gr">(a) Its area.</p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_uami5mw9">(b) The sizes of its angles.</p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_wfmhyxat"> 2. The area of triangle ABC is <m>28.1 \text{cm}^2</m> . It's side AB <m>= 7.2 \text{cm} </m> and    <m>\angle</m> ABC <m>= 48.6^\circ</m>. Find:</p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_lnstfgy0">(a) The length of the perpendicular from A to BC.</p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_s1djwkcc">(b) The length of BC.</p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_sxzhhnl3">
                     (a) Find the area using Heron's formula.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="triangle-example-one-solution">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    \draw[thick] (-2,0) -- (4,0) -- (2,2.6) -- cycle;
                    \node[left] at (-2,0) {F};
                    \node[right] at (4,0) {G};
                    \node[above] at (2,2.6) {H};
                    \node[below] at (-1.0,1.3) {\(9\) cm};
                    \node[below] at (3.3,1.8) {\(7\) cm};
                    \node[below] at (1.5,-0.3) {\(10\) cm};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
                <p xml:id="auto_vxdxbbrn">
                      <md>
          <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{(s(s - a)(s - b)(s - c))} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_4eyd7r53">
        <md>
          <mrow>s \amp = \frac{(a + b + c)}{2}</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_w5rdkujo">
        <md>
          <mrow>s \amp = \frac{(10+7+9)}{2}\, cm</mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_z883qs0c">
        <md>
          <mrow> \amp = 13 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_x8h8l1sf">
        Substitute in the values.
        <md>
          <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{(13(13 -10)(13 - 7)(13 - 9))} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_3q6kw001">
        <md>
          <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{(13 \text (6)\times(3)\times(4))} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_wjn6u95c">
        <md>
          <mrow>A \amp = \sqrt{936} </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_9x6iidy1">
        <md>
          <mrow> \amp = 30.6 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
        </md>
        The area of the triangle is <m>\, 30.6 \text{cm}^2</m>.
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_mlivuvv9">
      (b) Find the angles using the sine area formula.
      <me>
        A = \frac{1}{2} \,\text{ab sin C}
      </me>
      <me>
        A  = 30.6 \, \text{ cm}^2
      </me>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_93yzji6b">
        To find <m>\angle HFG</m> Using sides <m>a = 10</m> and <m>b =7 </m> and area<m> = 30.6 \,\text{cm}^2</m>
        <md>
            <mrow> 30.6 \, \text{cm}^2 = \amp \frac {1}{\cancel{2}} \times \cancel{10} \,  5\, \text{cm} \times 7\, \text{cm} \times \text{sin} \, A</mrow>
            <mrow>\text{Sin A} = \amp \frac{30.6 \cancel{\text{cm}}^2 \,\text{cm}}{35 \cancel{\text{cm}} }</mrow>
            <mrow> \text{sin A} = \amp 0.8743</mrow>
            <mrow> A = \amp sin^{-1} \,  {0.8743} </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp 60.96^\circ </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_9v7n5edj">
        To find <m>\angle FGH</m>  Using sides <m>a = 10</m> and <m>b =9 </m>and area<m> = 30.6 \,\text{cm}^2</m>
        <md>
            <mrow> 30.6 \, \text{cm}^2 = \amp \frac {1}{\cancel{2}} \times \cancel{10} \,  5\, \text{cm} \times 9\, \text{cm} \times \text{sin} \, C </mrow>
            <mrow>\text{Sin C} = \amp \frac{30.6 \cancel{\text{cm}}^2 \,\text{cm}}{45 \cancel{\text{cm}} }</mrow>
            <mrow> \text{sin C} = \amp 0.68</mrow>
            <mrow> C = \amp \text{sin}^{-1} {0.68} </mrow>
            <mrow> = \amp 42.84 ^\circ </mrow>
        </md>
      </p>
      <p xml:id="auto_gt5pgscc">
        To find the  <m>\angle GHF </m> we use the angle sum property.
      
      <md>
        <mrow> \angle GHF = \amp 180^\circ - (\angle FGH + \angle HFG)</mrow>
        <mrow> = \amp (180 - 103.80)^\circ</mrow>
        <mrow> = \amp 76.2^\circ</mrow>
      </md>
      Similarly we can use the Sin A rule which states that :
      <me>
       \frac{ \text{sin A}}{a} = \frac{ \text{sin B}}{b} = \frac{ \text{sin C}}{c}
      </me>
      
      </p>
