            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_2dd0lima">
                   (a) Find the length of the perpendicular from A to BC.
                </p>
                <image width="50%">
                <latex-image label="pretext-triangle">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                         % Triangle (c) - Right Triangle with Inner Triangle
                        \draw[thick] (4,-4) -- (10,-4) -- (6.5,-1) -- cycle;
                        \draw [thick](6.5,-4) -- (6.5,-1);
                        \node[left] at (4,-4) {B};
                        \node[right] at (10,-4) {C};
                        \node[above] at (6.5,-1) {A};
                        \node[left] at (6.5,-3){h};
                        \node[below] at (6.5,-4) {H};
                        \draw [thick] (6.2,-4) --(6.2,-3.7) --(6.7,-3.7) --(6.7,-4);
                        \node[left] at (5.2,-2.5) {7.2cm};
                        \node[right] at (6.5,-3.5) {A = 28.1 cm²};
                        \draw (5,-4) arc[start angle=0, end angle=60, radius=0.8];
                        \node at (5.5,-3.8) {\large 48.6°};
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p xml:id="auto_mzpw2bqc">
                    The formula for area using base and height.
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A = \amp\frac{1}{2} \times base \times height </mrow>
                        <mrow>28.1 \text{cm}^2 = \amp \frac{1}{2}\times b \times h </mrow>
                        <mrow> h = \amp \frac {2 \times 28.1}{BC} </mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_q8fzlemm">
                    (b) Finding BC using sine rule
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A =  \amp \frac{1}{2} \times AB \times BC \times \text{sin} \, \theta </mrow>
                        <mrow> 28.1 \,\text{cm}^2=\amp \frac{1}{2} \times 7.2\,\text{cm} \times BC \times \text{sin} \, \, 48.6^\circ </mrow>
                        <mrow> \text{sin} \, 48.6^\circ = \amp \, 0.7501</mrow>
                        <mrow> 28.1 \,\text{cm}^2=\amp \frac{1}{2} \times 7.2\, \text{cm}\times BC \times \text{sin} \, 0.7501 </mrow>
                        <mrow> BC = \amp \frac{28.1 \times 2}{7.2 \times 0.7501} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp 10.4 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_9d86zj2g">
                    Now substituting BC into the height equation :
                    <md>
                        <mrow> h = \amp  \frac{2 \times 28.1}{10.4}</mrow>
                        <mrow> =\amp 5.4 \,\text{cm}</mrow>
                    </md>
                   
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
